{"id":"d=origam-topic-4353//p=9c30ec7070734ee29cd5626e18bdb5cc","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4353"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["fc42515c3d5e40fb83169146416a6a16"],"__file_part":["1289679b6aa2412cbb0dcac2af561ccf"],"__part_n":["0"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"category":["docs"],"categoryId":["8"],"topicId":["4353"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-trace-workflows/4353"],"title":["How to trace workflows"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# How to trace workflows\n\nCategory: docs\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-trace-workflows/4353\n\n@vikter (2026-01-06 08:56:43Z):\n   \n This article demonstrates workflow tracing in ORIGAM. \n There are two types of workflows \u2014 sequential workflows and state workflows, however just the sequential workflows can be traced. \n A simple sequential workflow may consist of just a few steps and can be easy to follow. When working with more complex workflows containing many steps, data transformations, conditions, and similar logic, a proper tracing tool can be very useful. \n You can trace workflows that are executed directly in the Architect as well as workflows run in the client application. In both cases the tracing in the workflow properties needs to be turned on ( Trace  value is  Yes ). \n To achieve that you need to set the  Trace Level  to  Yes  or  InheritFromParent  (in that case the tracing value is inherited from the parent, when one workflow calls another): \n          image  377\u00D7291 36.3 KB         \n   The Trace Tool \n The tracing tool can be found in the main menu of the ORIGAM Architect:  Tools / Show Trace . \n The  Workflow Trace  screen consists of two sections. In the upper section, you can see all executions of all traced workflows, including execution time and the name of the user who ran them. The lower section shows the details of the selected run \u2013 all the steps: \n          Workflow Trace  1397\u00D7714 400 KB         \n For workflow selection in the upper section, it is useful to switch to the list view as shown in the picture. Otherwise, you would need to browse the workflows one by one. \n In the workflow step examiner below, you can also switch between a list view, where all workflow steps are visible, and a detail view, where you can inspect input and output data, for example: \n          Workflow step in detail view  982\u00D7488 171 KB         \n Notes: \n \n In the workflow list in the first picture, in the upper section under  Created By , you can see where the workflow was executed \u2014 either in the client application (username) or directly in the Architect (the Architect user is created when starting a new project). \n In the workflow step list in the first picture, note the  Subcategory  column. This is useful for identifying the first step that ended with an error, which is typically the main point of interest when troubleshooting a workflow. \n \n Here is a screenshot from a more sophisticated workflow: \n          image  1118\u00D7619 252 KB         \n Notes: \n \n Each step can be further divided and viewed in multiple lines \u2013 note the differences mainly in the  Subcategory  column. \n Subcategory  Input  contains all the input data for that particular step and  Result  shows the merged data.  Output  represents the data coming out from a transformation. \n In the  Remark  column you find information about the context store used in that step. \n The input or output data can be found in the  Data1  column, while in  Data2  you find information about parameters used. The data can be copied and used as input for testing transformations used in your workflows. \n \n   Limitations \n \n Currently  all UI steps are excluded from the tracing  \n \n\n---\n\n@vikter (2026-01-06 09:15:36Z):\n\n\n---\n\n@vikter (2026-02-09 14:03:19Z):\n If tracing stops working for any reason, you can reset it by deleting the settings file and then set Trace to \u201CYes\u201D again for your workflow. \n In a Linux-based Docker container, you can find this file here: \n /home/origam/projectData/model/RuntimeModelConfiguration.json  \n This file only specifies which workflows are to be traced; the tracing data itself is stored in a database and will not be affected by deleting the file.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-04-29T00:22:57"},"vector":[-0.014880436,-0.0078000897,-0.074372955,0.03193768,0.00866223,0.0067897458,0.0056778025,0.00499107,0.005531674,0.024909293,0.0031164025,-0.013620581,0.033608723,0.005237542,0.02385784,-0.032070957,-0.031379566,-0.0041213734,0.022982089,0.008018719,0.02749397,0.007506294,0.05810326,0.012382516,0.017229091,0.039639425,-0.030480472,-0.039296404,-0.00066425145,0.024343766,0.023537694,-0.015496579,0.039336443,-0.032373637,-0.020731734,-0.014793944,0.0150491735,0.0063701933,-0.016148807,0.028400155,-0.014008416,0.0064539644,0.019086141,-0.022429656,0.017978292,-0.022018228,-0.010067115,-0.0023241446,-0.0010332834,-0.063201666,-0.03268261,-0.015631558,0.020047378,-0.03727931,-0.0014821922,0.039252583,-0.049215518,-0.04697066,-0.078007646,0.045989133,-0.026270332,0.008770389,-0.003515125,-0.022701299,0.00090546964,0.023375029,-0.028988693,0.01981137,-0.017537057,-0.01763174,0.012365232,0.0048682503,-0.073893,-0.030308079,-0.05684474,0.012171146,0.024398956,-0.016505875,0.0069984337,0.024903348,-0.011116762,0.01922897,0.033873525,0.012051559,-0.021486513,0.00064068247,-0.018064125,0.020255955,0.015145987,0.032376587,-0.017045291,-0.050287355,0.005570905,-0.030610543,-0.029010024,0.020870402,0.016710099,-0.0026309625,0.029401928,0.023971137,-0.02339107,-0.05846112,-0.03360055,0.02258558,-0.028469976,-0.024908213,0.043317992,-0.028455488,-0.0070340945,-0.053127673,0.015886927,-0.008084619,0.02234602,-0.003389105,0.0016807915,-0.018942323,-0.018075157,-0.031022878,-0.016524302,-0.019977791,0.008766358,-0.0055465344,0.0